ns emerges. Like a casino of love, the host club is a site of desperation, aspiration, and hope, in which both hosts and clients are eager to roll the dice. Takeyama reveals the aspirational mode not only of the host club, but also of a Japanese society built on the commercialization of aspiration, seducing its citizens out of the present and into a future where hopes and dreams are imaginable-and billions of dollars can be made.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aLovexEconomic aspectsxJapanxTokyo. 0aLovexEconomic aspectszJapanzTokyo. 0aMan-woman relationshipsxJapanxTokyo. 0aMan-woman relationshipszJapanzTokyo. 0aNightclubsxJapanxTokyo. 0aNightclubszJapanzTokyo. 0aSex-oriented businessesxJapanxTokyo. 0aSex-oriented businesseszJapanzTokyo. 0aSexual ethicsxJapanxTokyo. 0aSexual ethicszJapanzTokyo. 4aJapan. 4aanthropology of future. 4acommodified romance. 4aflexible labor. 4agender and sexuality. 4aglobalization. 4alifestyle consumption. 4aneoliberal subjectivity. 4aseduction. 4aservice economy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479855640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804798556423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804798556.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles